AB  - During Allende's revolutionary socialism (1970-73), Chile experienced a subversive moment that overturned some of the hierarchical divisions of society and harnessed the creative capacities of those who had been marginalized from artistic and creative labor. The supporters of the socialist government--workers, students, activists, artists, and intellectuals--dared to redefine the hierarchical bounds by envisioning a different world. Cultural workers realized that the existing dominant culture and educational system was adverse to socialism, and they spearheaded a new political culture in which critical thinking was a focal point to incite political activism. The architects and organizers of this new political culture, although a heterogeneous group with different perspectives of thought and practice, shared two important points of confluence: They were critical of the existing order of oppression, and they were agents of change. They argued that the ruling ideology, the educational system, and the mainstream national identity tended to reinforce upper-class prejudices and cultural discrimination against the interests of the popular classes, the classes "of the people."
